<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="579" type="materials_examined">
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,332,1149]" box="[199,719,439,464]" pageId="2" pageNumber="579">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,310,439,464]" pageId="2" pageNumber="579">Material.</emphasis>
One whole mount (HU nr. VI. 
<number box="[653,707,440,464]" pageId="2" pageNumber="579" value="3.17">3.17</number>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,332,1149]" pageId="2" pageNumber="579">
Small animal with eyes. The stylet of this individual is 
<number box="[820,848,476,501]" pageId="2" pageNumber="579" value="35.0">35</number>
µm long, measured along line a; it is 
<number box="[1274,1302,476,500]" pageId="2" pageNumber="579" value="20.0">20</number>
µm wide at the proximal opening, tapering to 
<number box="[535,549,512,536]" pageId="2" pageNumber="579" value="2.0">2</number>
µm width after 
<number box="[732,760,512,536]" pageId="2" pageNumber="579" value="19.0">19</number>
µm, where it bends over 
<number box="[1049,1079,512,536]" pageId="2" pageNumber="579" value="90.0">90</number>
° to a spine of 
<number box="[1242,1270,511,536]" pageId="2" pageNumber="579" value="16.0">16</number>
µm length. Its length, measured along lines b and c is 
<number box="[594,622,548,572]" pageId="2" pageNumber="579" value="22.0">22</number>
µm and 
<number box="[721,749,548,572]" pageId="2" pageNumber="579" value="24.0">24</number>
µm, respectively. The prostate glands have their necks in the proximal part of the stylet and in the prostate vesicle.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,332,1149]" pageId="2" pageNumber="579">
With the data available, it is impossible to identify this individual to the species level. A hook-shaped stylet is found in several species of 
<taxonomicName box="[454,615,657,680]" class="Rhabditophora" family="Macrostomidae" genus="Macrostomum" kingdom="Animalia" order="Macrostomida" pageId="2" pageNumber="579" phylum="Platyhelminthes" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[454,615,657,680]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="579">Macrostomum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and slight differences may occur in size and shape, also depending on the degree of compression under the cover slip. Moreover, I cannot provide data on the living animal.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,332,1149]" pageId="2" pageNumber="579">
The size of the stylet of the individual from the Ria 
<collectingCountry box="[839,937,728,751]" name="Taiwan" pageId="2" pageNumber="579">Formosa</collectingCountry>
is close to that of 
<taxonomicName authority="Ax, 1951" authorityName="Ax" authorityYear="1951" box="[1175,1436,727,752]" class="Rhabditophora" family="Macrostomidae" genus="Macrostomum" kingdom="Animalia" order="Macrostomida" pageId="2" pageNumber="579" phylum="Platyhelminthes" rank="species" species="pusillum">
<emphasis box="[1175,1314,728,752]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="579">M. pusillum</emphasis>
Ax, 
<number box="[1380,1436,727,752]" pageId="2" pageNumber="579" value="1951.0">1951</number>
</taxonomicName>
(
<number box="[159,229,764,789]" pageId="2" pageNumber="579" value="25.0" valueMax="26.0" valueMin="24.0">24–26</number>
µm). However, it lacks the characteristic dots in the stylet. 
<bibRefCitation author="Mack-Fira" box="[890,1089,764,789]" pageId="2" pageNumber="579" refString="Mack-Fira, V. (1971) Deux Turbellaries nouveaux de la Mer Noire. Revue Roumaine de Biologie, serie Zoologie, 16 (4), 233 - 240." type="journal article" year="1971">
Mack-Fira (
<number box="[1023,1081,764,788]" pageId="2" pageNumber="579" value="1971.0">1971</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
describes 
<taxonomicName box="[1206,1335,765,788]" class="Rhabditophora" family="Macrostomidae" genus="Macrostomum" kingdom="Animalia" order="Macrostomida" pageId="2" pageNumber="579" phylum="Platyhelminthes" rank="species" species="peteraxi">
<emphasis box="[1206,1335,765,788]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="579">M. peteraxi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from the Danube estuary with a stylet of similar length (
<number box="[678,748,800,824]" pageId="2" pageNumber="579" value="28.5" valueMax="30.0" valueMin="27.0">27–30</number>
µm) but, as stated by 
<bibRefCitation author="Rieger" box="[997,1156,799,824]" pageId="2" pageNumber="579" refString="Rieger, R. M. (1977) The relationship of Character Variability and Morphological Complexity in Copulatory Structures of Turbellaria-Macrostomida and Haplopharyngida. Mikrofuana des Meeresboden, 61, 197 - 216." type="journal article" year="1977">
Rieger (
<number box="[1088,1148,800,824]" pageId="2" pageNumber="579" value="1977.0">1977</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
, her figures do not allow a precise comparison. On the other hand, the stylet of this animal is slightly smaller than that of representatives of 
<taxonomicName authority="Beklemischev, 1951" authorityName="Beklemischev" authorityYear="1951" box="[151,568,871,896]" class="Rhabditophora" family="Macrostomidae" genus="Macrostomum" kingdom="Animalia" order="Macrostomida" pageId="2" pageNumber="579" phylum="Platyhelminthes" rank="species" species="hystricinum">
<emphasis box="[151,320,872,896]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="579">M. hystricinum</emphasis>
Beklemischev, 
<number box="[508,568,871,896]" pageId="2" pageNumber="579" value="1951.0">1951</number>
</taxonomicName>
: 
<bibRefCitation author="Ax" box="[584,705,872,896]" pageId="2" pageNumber="579" refString="Ax, P. (2008) Plathelminthes aus Brackgewassern der Nordhalbkugel. Akademie der Wissenschaften und der Literatur, Abh. Mathematisch-naturwissenschaftlichen Klasse (2008), 1, 696 pp." type="book" year="2008">
Ax (
<number box="[638,697,872,896]" pageId="2" pageNumber="579" value="2008.0">2008</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
gives lengths of 
<number box="[917,985,872,896]" pageId="2" pageNumber="579" value="35.5" valueMax="41.0" valueMin="30.0">30–41</number>
µm for the European populations and 
<number box="[151,219,908,933]" pageId="2" pageNumber="579" value="37.5" valueMax="40.0" valueMin="35.0">35–40</number>
µm for the Canadian populations; 
<bibRefCitation author="Rieger" box="[622,780,908,933]" pageId="2" pageNumber="579" refString="Rieger, R. M. (1977) The relationship of Character Variability and Morphological Complexity in Copulatory Structures of Turbellaria-Macrostomida and Haplopharyngida. Mikrofuana des Meeresboden, 61, 197 - 216." type="journal article" year="1977">
Rieger (
<number box="[714,772,908,932]" pageId="2" pageNumber="579" value="1977.0">1977</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
gives lengths of 
<number box="[981,1050,908,932]" pageId="2" pageNumber="579" value="36.0" valueMax="42.0" valueMin="30.0">30–42</number>
µm for the N. American Atlantic populations and 
<number box="[342,410,944,968]" pageId="2" pageNumber="579" value="35.5" valueMax="38.0" valueMin="33.0">33–38</number>
µm for the Ligurian population. When considering the ratio length/proximal diameter, it appears that the length is about 
<number box="[507,542,980,1004]" pageId="2" pageNumber="579" value="2.2">2.2</number>
times the proximal diameter in 
<taxonomicName box="[901,1036,980,1004]" class="Rhabditophora" family="Macrostomidae" genus="Macrostomum" kingdom="Animalia" order="Macrostomida" pageId="2" pageNumber="579" phylum="Platyhelminthes" rank="species" species="pusillum">
<emphasis box="[901,1036,980,1004]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="579">M. pusillum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and in 
<taxonomicName box="[1119,1249,981,1004]" class="Rhabditophora" family="Macrostomidae" genus="Macrostomum" kingdom="Animalia" order="Macrostomida" pageId="2" pageNumber="579" phylum="Platyhelminthes" rank="species" species="peteraxi">
<emphasis box="[1119,1249,981,1004]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="579">M. peteraxi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<number box="[1304,1339,980,1005]" pageId="2" pageNumber="579" value="1.5">1.5</number>
times in 
<taxonomicName box="[151,320,1016,1040]" class="Rhabditophora" family="Macrostomidae" genus="Macrostomum" kingdom="Animalia" order="Macrostomida" pageId="2" pageNumber="579" phylum="Platyhelminthes" rank="species" species="hystricinum">
<emphasis box="[151,320,1016,1040]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="579">M. hystricinum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. In the Faro animal the ratio is about 
<number box="[744,756,1016,1040]" pageId="2" pageNumber="579" value="1.0">1</number>
/ 
<number box="[769,781,1016,1040]" pageId="2" pageNumber="579" value="1.0">1</number>
. It has most similarity with the stylet of 
<taxonomicName box="[1236,1397,1017,1040]" class="Rhabditophora" family="Macrostomidae" genus="Macrostomum" kingdom="Animalia" order="Macrostomida" pageId="2" pageNumber="579" phylum="Platyhelminthes" rank="genus" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[1236,1397,1017,1040]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="579">Macrostomum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel pageId="2" pageNumber="579" rank="species">
sp. 
<date box="[151,199,1053,1076]" pageId="2" pageNumber="579">nov.</date>
</taxonomicNameLabel>
<number box="[204,218,1052,1076]" pageId="2" pageNumber="579" value="1.0">1</number>
(specimen accession code MTP LS 
<number box="[623,666,1052,1076]" pageId="2" pageNumber="579" value="302.0">302</number>
) used by 
<bibRefCitation box="[774,1005,1052,1077]" pageId="2" pageNumber="579" refString="Scharer, L., Littlewood, D. T. J., Waeschenbach, A., Yoshidac, W. &amp; Vizosoa, D. B. (2011) Mating behavior and the evolution of sperm design. Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences of the United States, 108 (4), 1490 - 1495. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1073 / pnas. 1013892108" type="journal article">
Schärer 
<emphasis box="[866,913,1052,1076]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="579">et al</emphasis>
. (
<number box="[936,996,1052,1076]" pageId="2" pageNumber="579" value="2011.0">2011</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
. The length of the stylet in this species is 
<number box="[178,206,1088,1112]" pageId="2" pageNumber="579" value="28.0">28</number>
µm and the proximal diameter is 
<number box="[591,619,1088,1112]" pageId="2" pageNumber="579" value="24.0">24</number>
µm. With the data now available it is, however, impossible to say if the same species is concerned. In all other species with a similar shape of the stylet, this stylet is considerably larger.
</paragraph>
